<?php
$biasOptions = array("a" => "Undercoverage", "b" => "Convenience sampling", "c" => "Voluntary response", "d" => "Nonresponse", "e" => "Response bias", "f" => "Wording bias", "g" => "Survivorship bias");

return array(
    "overview" => "Bias is a systematic problem in how data are selected, measured, or reported. This lesson teaches you to identify the mechanism, predict who is missing or overrepresented, and redesign the study rather than merely naming the bias.",
    "objectives" => array(
        "Distinguish systematic bias from ordinary sampling variability.",
        "Identify undercoverage, convenience, voluntary-response, nonresponse, response, wording, and survivorship bias.",
        "Predict a likely direction of bias when the context supports one.",
        "Rewrite leading, double-barrelled, vague, or unbalanced questions.",
        "Redesign a biased sampling or survey procedure."
    ),
    "prerequisites" => array(
        "Identify the population and sample in a study.",
        "Recognize random and non-random sampling methods.",
        "Compare a sample estimate with an unknown population value."
    ),
    "vocabulary" => array(
        array("Bias", "A systematic tendency for a method to overestimate, underestimate, or otherwise misrepresent the target."),
        array("Sampling variability", "Natural sample-to-sample change caused by selecting different individuals through chance."),
        array("Undercoverage", "Some population groups have little or no chance to be selected."),
        array("Convenience sample", "A sample made from individuals who are easiest to reach."),
        array("Voluntary response", "People choose themselves into a sample, often because they have strong opinions."),
        array("Nonresponse", "Selected individuals do not provide usable data."),
        array("Response bias", "Recorded answers differ systematically from the truth."),
        array("Wording bias", "Question wording or ordering pushes responses in a direction or makes them unclear."),
        array("Survivorship bias", "Analysis focuses only on cases that remain visible after a selection or failure process."),
        array("Direction of bias", "Whether a method is likely to make an estimate too high, too low, or uncertain in direction.")
    ),
    "sections" => array(
        array("title" => "Bias Is Systematic, Not Merely Wrong", "content" => array(
            "<p>Different random samples naturally produce different statistics. One random sample might estimate an average study time of 5.8 hours and another 6.1 hours. That movement is <strong>sampling variability</strong>. It has no fixed direction and becomes smaller, on average, as random sample size increases. <strong>Bias</strong> is different: something in the method consistently pushes estimates away from the target or represents the wrong mix of individuals.</p>",
            "<p>A result can be inaccurate without proving bias. A fair random sample may happen to land high or low. To diagnose bias, identify a mechanism: Who could not be selected? Who chose to participate? Who failed to respond? Why might an answer be inaccurate? What wording steered the response? Without a mechanism, \"the answer seems wrong\" is not enough evidence.</p>",
            array("type" => "example", "label" => "Precision can be precisely wrong", "html" => "<p>Imagine a ruler whose zero mark is misplaced by 1 cm. Measuring a table 100,000 times reduces random variation in the average reading, but the average remains about 1 cm wrong. Likewise, a huge biased sample can estimate the wrong population value very precisely.</p>"),
            "<p>Bias does not always make an estimate too high. It may make it too low, or the direction may be impossible to predict. A strong explanation links the missing or inaccurate responses to the measured variable. If library users are surveyed about reading time, the estimate is plausibly too high because people in the library may read more. If a group is missing but its likely answers are unknown, state that the direction cannot be determined.</p>"
        )),
        array("title" => "Selection Bias: Who Gets a Chance?", "content" => array(
            "<p><strong>Undercoverage</strong> occurs when parts of the population are absent or much less likely to enter the sample. A technology survey delivered only through a smartphone app undercovers students without compatible phones. Calling only landlines undercovers people who use mobile phones only. Surveying students at after-school sports undercovers those who leave school early, work, receive support elsewhere, or do not play sports.</p>",
            "<p>A <strong>convenience sample</strong> selects whoever is easiest to contact: nearby friends, the first ten customers, or students in the front row. Convenience is fast, but location and availability may be connected to the outcome. A teacher asking only an advanced class about homework difficulty is unlikely to represent the entire school.</p>",
            "<p>A <strong>voluntary-response sample</strong> invites people to opt in through an online poll, call-in show, review form, or public post. People with unusually strong positive or negative opinions are more likely to respond, so moderate views may be underrepresented. Voluntary response differs from a random sample with nonresponse: in voluntary response, there was no probability-selected starting sample.</p>",
            array("type" => "warning", "label" => "Name the mechanism, not just 'sampling bias'", "html" => "<p>Write: \"This is undercoverage because students without smartphones cannot receive the survey. Their technology access may differ, so the estimate may be too high.\" The explanation earns more than a broad label.</p>")
        )),
        array("title" => "Participation and Answer Bias", "content" => array(
            "<p><strong>Nonresponse</strong> begins after researchers select individuals. Some cannot be contacted, refuse, skip important questions, or leave before providing data. Missing responses create bias when nonresponders differ from responders on the variable of interest. In a homework survey, students who complete little homework may be less willing to answer, making the reported completion rate too high.</p>",
            "<p><strong>Response bias</strong> occurs when people provide inaccurate answers. Sensitive topics, embarrassment, fear of judgment, social desirability, poor memory, lack of privacy, and interviewer influence can all change responses. Students may overreport study time to appear responsible or underreport rule-breaking. Anonymous collection can reduce pressure, but it cannot guarantee accurate memory or understanding.</p>",
            "<p>Nonresponse and response bias should not be confused. A nonresponding person supplies no usable answer. A response-biased person supplies an answer that may not reflect the truth. A study can contain both: some selected users ignore a survey, while others who answer exaggerate how often they use the app.</p>",
            array("type" => "note", "label" => "Practical protections", "html" => "<p>Use repeated contact attempts, short clear surveys, multiple response modes, neutral interviewers, privacy protection, and validation against records when ethical and appropriate. No single protection removes every form of bias.</p>")
        )),
        array("title" => "Question Wording and Order", "content" => array(
            "<p>Questions should let respondents understand the same task and express a view without being pushed. Loaded language such as \"outdated and dangerous computers\" suggests the desired answer. A neutral version asks, \"Do you support or oppose replacing the school's current computers?\" Balanced options should represent both sides with similar wording and detail.</p>",
            "<p>A <strong>double-barrelled question</strong> asks about two issues at once: \"Are you satisfied with the homework policy and grading system?\" A student may approve of one and dislike the other. Split it into two questions. Double negatives, vague time periods, and undefined words such as \"often\" also create inconsistent interpretation. Ask \"During the past seven days, on how many days...?\" instead of \"Do you usually...?\"</p>",
            "<p>Question order can prime later responses. Asking people to list every delay they experienced before rating transit satisfaction may produce a lower rating than asking the rating first. Randomizing order, separating topics, and pilot-testing the questionnaire can reveal these effects. The goal is not to remove all context, which is impossible, but to avoid avoidable influence.</p>",
            array("type" => "definition", "label" => "Neutral does not mean vague", "html" => "<p>A neutral question can still be specific: define the time period, behaviour, unit, and balanced response choices without adding approving or disapproving language.</p>")
        )),
        array("title" => "Survivorship and Participation Effects", "content" => array(
            "<p><strong>Survivorship bias</strong> studies only cases that remain visible. Analysing successful businesses to discover what all startups should do ignores failed businesses that may have used the same strategies. Studying only students who finished a difficult program hides the experiences of those who withdrew. Analysing active app users alone cannot explain why all original users stayed or left.</p>",
            "<p>Participation effects create a related warning. Students who voluntarily join a study-skills program may already be more motivated, have more support, or be more concerned about their grades. If they improve, the program may help, but self-selection prevents researchers from attributing the entire change to the program. Comparison groups and random assignment are needed for stronger causal evidence.</p>",
            "<p>A thoughtful redesign begins with the target population and works backward. Build a sampling frame that covers the population, use a probability method, contact selected individuals in several ways, write neutral single-purpose questions, and report response rates and limitations. When records are filtered, identify who disappeared and why. Transparency does not erase bias, but it helps readers judge the evidence.</p>"
        ))
    ),
    "worked_examples" => array(
        array("title" => "Library reading survey", "scenario" => "A school surveys students in the library at lunch to estimate weekly reading time for all students.", "steps" => array("The target population is all students, but only students visiting the library at lunch can be selected.", "Library visitors may read more than students who do not visit, creating undercoverage and convenience bias.", "Because the overrepresented group is plausibly more active in reading, the estimated reading time is likely too high.", "A better design is to randomly sample student IDs from the full enrolment list and offer several private response times."), "conclusion" => "The location excludes relevant groups and plausibly overestimates school-wide reading time."),
        array("title" => "Optional product review", "scenario" => "After a purchase, customers may click an optional link to rate a product.", "steps" => array("Customers decide for themselves whether to enter the sample, so this is voluntary response.", "People with very good or very bad experiences may respond more often than people with moderate experiences.", "The direction is not necessarily known because both positive and negative extremes may be overrepresented.", "Randomly invite a defined sample and follow up with selected customers to improve representation."), "conclusion" => "The average of optional reviews may not represent all buyers, even when thousands of reviews are posted."),
        array("title" => "Homework nonresponse", "scenario" => "A random sample of students receives a homework survey, but only 42% respond.", "steps" => array("The initial selection was random, so the issue is not voluntary response.", "Most selected students supplied no data, creating potential nonresponse bias.", "Students who complete little homework may avoid the survey, which would push the estimated completion rate upward.", "Use reminders, brief questionnaires, multiple response modes, and compare known characteristics of responders and nonresponders."), "conclusion" => "Random selection does not protect a study when selected groups respond at meaningfully different rates."),
        array("title" => "Repairing a leading question", "scenario" => "A poll asks, 'Should the school finally stop wasting money on unpopular assemblies?'", "steps" => array("The words finally, wasting, and unpopular communicate a negative judgment.", "The question also assumes the spending is wasteful and the assemblies are unpopular.", "Remove assumptions and offer balanced choices: 'Do you support or oppose continuing the current school assembly program?'", "A follow-up can separately ask why the respondent chose that view."), "conclusion" => "Neutral wording measures opinion instead of supplying one."),
        array("title" => "Only successful users", "scenario" => "A company studies users who maintained a 100-day streak to decide which onboarding method works best for every new user.", "steps" => array("The analysis excludes users who stopped before 100 days.", "Onboarding may affect both remaining visible and leaving, so the omitted group is essential.", "This is survivorship bias.", "Compare all users originally assigned to each onboarding method, including inactive accounts, and define retention before analysis."), "conclusion" => "Studying only survivors cannot reveal the full effect of onboarding on all new users."),
    ),
    "misconceptions" => array(
        array("Any inaccurate result is biased.", "Chance alone can make an unbiased random sample differ from the population. Bias requires a systematic mechanism."),
        array("A large sample is unbiased.", "Size reduces random variability. It does not restore groups excluded by the data-collection method."),
        array("Anonymous surveys cannot have response bias.", "Anonymity may reduce social pressure but cannot eliminate confusion, memory errors, exaggeration, or deliberate inaccuracy."),
        array("Voluntary response and nonresponse are identical.", "Voluntary responders opt into an open invitation; nonresponders were selected but fail to provide data."),
        array("Bias always pushes an estimate upward.", "Bias may push high, push low, distort categories, or have an uncertain direction."),
        array("Random sampling removes every bias.", "It addresses selection, but nonresponse, wording, measurement, and response problems can remain.")
    ),
    "why" => array(
        "Bias can turn an impressive sample size or polished chart into a misleading claim. Schools may allocate resources poorly, businesses may misunderstand customers, and public polls may report opinions that the selection method helped create.",
        "The useful habit is a three-part diagnosis: name the mechanism, identify who or what is misrepresented, and explain the likely effect on the estimate. That habit transfers to nearly every later statistics topic."
    ),
    "knowledge_check" => array(
        stats_classify("kc1", "A news site posts an open poll and reports the results as public opinion.", $biasOptions, "c", "<p>Readers choose themselves into the sample, making this voluntary response.</p>", "Did researchers select people, or did people opt in?", "foundational", array("bias")),
        stats_classify("kc2", "A random sample is chosen, but 60% of selected people never answer.", $biasOptions, "d", "<p>Selected individuals fail to provide data, which is nonresponse.</p>", "They were selected before they failed to answer.", "foundational", array("bias")),
        stats_classify("kc3", "A study of app success includes only accounts still active after one year.", $biasOptions, "g", "<p>Inactive accounts disappeared from the analysed group, creating survivorship bias.</p>", "Who is no longer visible?", "foundational", array("bias"))
    ),
    "guided_practice" => array(
        stats_classify("g1", "A city opinion survey calls landlines only.", $biasOptions, "a", "<p>Residents without landlines have no chance to be selected, so the frame undercovers them.</p>", "Identify the missing communication group.", "foundational", array("undercoverage")),
        stats_classify("g2", "A student asks five close friends which lunch should be served.", $biasOptions, "b", "<p>The easiest nearby people are selected, creating convenience sampling bias.</p>", "Friends were chosen for access, not chance.", "foundational", array("convenience")),
        stats_classify("g3", "Students report fewer rule violations when the principal conducts face-to-face interviews.", $biasOptions, "e", "<p>Fear of judgment or consequences may produce inaccurate answers, a form of response bias.</p>", "The answers are recorded, but may not be truthful.", "proficient", array("response bias")),
        stats_classify("g4", "A survey asks, 'Do you support the sensible plan to improve school safety?'", $biasOptions, "f", "<p>The approving word sensible pushes respondents toward support, creating wording bias.</p>", "Look for judgment inside the question.", "foundational", array("wording")),
        stats_written("g5", "short-response", "Predict the direction of bias when gym members are surveyed to estimate exercise time for all city residents.", "<p><strong>Model answer:</strong> The estimate will likely be too high because gym members are overrepresented and probably exercise more than residents who do not belong to a gym.</p>", "Connect the selected location with the measured behaviour.", "proficient", array("direction")),
        stats_written("g6", "short-response", "Rewrite: 'How satisfied are you with the school's homework policy and grading system?'", "<p><strong>Model answer:</strong> Split it: 'How satisfied are you with the school's homework policy?' and 'How satisfied are you with the school's grading system?' Give each the same balanced response scale.</p>", "The original asks about two topics.", "proficient", array("wording")),
        stats_written("g7", "error-analysis", "A student says a sample of 50,000 social-media followers cannot be biased because it is large. Explain the error.", "<p><strong>Model answer:</strong> Followers may differ systematically from the target population. Large size reduces random variation within the follower group but does not include people outside that group.</p>", "Size and selection method solve different problems.", "proficient", array("sample size", "bias")),
        stats_written("g8", "short-response", "Redesign a smartphone-only survey intended to represent every student.", "<p><strong>Model answer:</strong> Randomly select students from the full school roster, then allow selected students to respond through a school computer, paper form, or phone. Follow up privately with nonresponders.</p>", "Repair both coverage and participation.", "advanced", array("redesign"))
    ),
    "independent_practice" => array(
        stats_classify("i1", "An optional radio call-in question asks listeners to rate the host.", $biasOptions, "c", "<p>Listeners with strong views choose to call, so this is voluntary response.</p>", "Open opt-in participation.", "foundational", array("voluntary response")),
        stats_classify("i2", "A school survey is emailed to every selected student, but students with low attendance rarely reply.", $biasOptions, "d", "<p>The low-attendance students were selected but respond less often, creating nonresponse bias.</p>", "They are in the sample before failing to answer.", "proficient", array("nonresponse")),
        stats_classify("i3", "A study of business strategy analyses only companies that are still operating.", $biasOptions, "g", "<p>Failed companies are invisible in the analysis, which is survivorship bias.</p>", "The missing cases did not survive.", "foundational", array("survivorship")),
        stats_classify("i4", "A question uses a double negative that respondents misunderstand.", $biasOptions, "f", "<p>Confusing wording changes how answers are interpreted, so this is wording bias.</p>", "The problem is the sentence itself.", "foundational", array("wording")),
        stats_written("i5", "short-response", "Predict the direction of bias when a homework-completion survey is given only in an after-school tutoring room.", "<p><strong>Model answer:</strong> The direction is uncertain without more context. Tutoring students might complete more because they seek help, or less because they are struggling. The sample is still biased even when direction is unclear.</p>", "Do not invent a direction when two plausible effects compete.", "advanced", array("direction")),
        stats_written("i6", "short-response", "Rewrite: 'Do you agree that the city should finally repair its dangerous parks?'", "<p><strong>Model answer:</strong> 'Do you support or oppose increasing city spending to repair public parks?' A separate question can ask respondents to rate current park conditions.</p>", "Remove emotionally loaded assumptions.", "proficient", array("wording")),
        stats_written("i7", "short-response", "Rewrite: 'Do you not disagree that students should not lose free periods?'", "<p><strong>Model answer:</strong> 'Do you support or oppose allowing students to keep their current free periods?'</p>", "Replace the double negatives with one direct action.", "proficient", array("wording")),
        stats_written("i8", "short-response", "A study asks active app users about why people stop using the app. Identify and repair the central problem.", "<p><strong>Model answer:</strong> Active users cannot fully represent users who left, creating survivorship and undercoverage problems. Sample from all accounts created during a defined period and contact both active and inactive users through available consented methods.</p>", "The people who can explain leaving are missing.", "advanced", array("survivorship", "redesign")),
        stats_written("i9", "short-response", "Explain why a neutral question can still produce response bias.", "<p><strong>Model answer:</strong> Even neutral wording cannot guarantee truthful or accurate answers. Sensitive topics, memory limits, interviewer presence, or fear that privacy will be lost can distort responses.</p>", "Wording is only one part of data collection.", "proficient", array("response bias")),
        stats_written("i10", "short-response", "A school posts a leading online poll, receives few responses, and analyses only students still enrolled. Identify three biases and propose one repair for each.", "<p><strong>Model answer:</strong> The open poll creates voluntary-response bias; use a random roster sample. Few selected responses would create nonresponse; follow up and offer modes. Leading wording creates wording bias; rewrite neutrally. Restricting to still-enrolled students may create survivorship or undercoverage; define the population and include former students when the question concerns them.</p>", "Trace selection, participation, wording, and filtering separately.", "advanced", array("multiple bias", "redesign"))
    ),
    "summary" => array(
        "Bias is a systematic feature of a method; sampling variability is ordinary chance fluctuation.",
        "Undercoverage, convenience, and voluntary response affect who enters a sample.",
        "Nonresponse and response bias affect whether selected people provide accurate usable data.",
        "Wording, ordering, and double-barrelled questions can shape answers.",
        "A complete bias analysis identifies the mechanism, affected group, likely direction, and a realistic repair."
    ),
    "exit_ticket" => array(
        stats_written("e1", "short-response", "Distinguish voluntary response from nonresponse with one sentence for each.", "<p><strong>Model answer:</strong> In voluntary response, people choose themselves into an open sample. In nonresponse, researchers select individuals first, but some selected individuals do not supply data.</p>", "Focus on when selection occurs.", "proficient", array("bias")),
        stats_written("e2", "short-response", "Why does increasing sample size fail to remove undercoverage?", "<p><strong>Model answer:</strong> A larger sample selects more people from the same incomplete frame. Individuals who have no chance to enter remain missing, so the systematic distortion remains.</p>", "Imagine repeating the same flawed selection many more times.", "proficient", array("sample size", "undercoverage"))
    )
);
